518
00:34:15,250 --> 00:34:17,070
You better settle down, Levi Jackson.

519
00:34:17,280 --> 00:34:21,300
Lest you want this female's mind
right here, in front of everybody.

520
00:34:22,680 --> 00:34:24,130
All I'm saying

521
00:34:24,730 --> 00:34:26,480
Don't play the fool.

522
00:34:26,650 --> 00:34:28,410
I don't want to see you get hurt.

523
00:34:28,690 --> 00:34:30,683
NASA's never ever given you gals your due,

524
00:34:30,708 --> 00:34:32,994
having a couple of extra degrees
ain't gonna change that.

525
00:34:34,910 --> 00:34:36,870
Civil rights ain't always civil.

526
00:34:42,650 --> 00:34:44,410
I don't want any greens either.

527
00:34:44,500 --> 00:34:47,330
No lip, little miss. Your brother
gets them, and so do you.

528
00:34:50,220 --> 00:34:52,000
I hear he's planning on staying
in the area.

529
00:34:54,020 --> 00:34:55,340
Well. That's good for him.

530
00:34:56,164 --> 00:34:58,470
Katherine,
go find your way over there.

531
00:34:58,720 --> 00:35:01,890
That Colonel Jim is a tall glass of water

532
00:35:01,914 --> 00:35:05,714
That he is.
Tall. Strong. Commanding.

533
00:35:05,738 --> 00:35:09,238
- And I bet he's like that day and night.
- Mary

534
00:35:09,450 --> 00:35:12,490
It's Sunday
Please, have some shame.

535
00:35:12,640 --> 00:35:13,910
I will not.

536
00:35:14,610 --> 00:35:18,190
- Mm. I think he's smiling over here.
- At you

537
00:35:22,550 --> 00:35:26,630
- I'm not smiling back.
- You're all teeth right now.

538
00:35:26,654 --> 00:35:27,754
I am not

539
00:35:30,080 --> 00:35:32,600
- He's coming over
- Now, why would he be doing that?

540
00:35:32,610 --> 00:35:35,210
- Because Mary's waving at him
- No! Ladies, I'm not..

541
00:35:35,290 --> 00:35:36,820
Too late. Fix your hair on the side.

542
00:35:38,400 --> 00:35:41,548
I'm Dorothy Vaughan. That's Mary Jackson.
I believe you met her husband, Levi.

543
00:35:41,573 --> 00:35:43,110
Yes, ma'am. Good to meet you all.

544
00:35:43,111 --> 00:35:44,835
And Ms. Katherine Goble.

545
00:35:45,160 --> 00:35:46,650
She's not married. She's a widow.

546
00:35:47,270 --> 00:35:49,050
With three beautiful little girls,

547
00:35:49,200 --> 00:35:51,870
so well-behaved.
Angels on earth, is what we'd like to call 'em.

548
00:35:52,920 --> 00:35:56,040
- Dorothy, slice-a pie?
- I'd love one

549
00:35:56,264 --> 00:35:57,669
Excuse me

550
00:35:57,870 --> 00:35:59,530
You already have a slice-a pie, Doro..

551
00:36:03,780 --> 00:36:05,092
Well, I was just

552
00:36:05,117 --> 00:36:07,814
- fixing my three babies some plates.
- May I help?

553
00:36:08,790 --> 00:36:10,360
Sure.
Ah! Fruit salad!

554
00:36:13,830 --> 00:36:16,080
Pastor mentioned you're computer
at NASA

555
00:36:16,990 --> 00:36:19,050
- Yes
- What's that entail?

556
00:36:21,140 --> 00:36:23,552
We calculate the mathematics
necessary to enable

557
00:36:23,577 --> 00:36:25,644
launch and landing for
the Space Program.

558
00:36:27,490 --> 00:36:29,820
- Pretty heady stuff!
- Yes, it is.

559
00:36:29,860 --> 00:36:31,400
They let women handle that sort of..

560
00:36:34,700 --> 00:36:36,760
That's.. Not what I mean

561
00:36:37,020 --> 00:36:38,350
What do you mean?

562
00:36:41,340 --> 00:36:47,330
I am.. Just surprised something so..
Taxing

563
00:36:47,770 --> 00:36:49,070
Mr. Johnson

564
00:36:50,550 --> 00:36:52,710
If I were you, I'd quit talking right now

565
00:36:52,790 --> 00:36:54,420
I don't mean any disrespect

566
00:36:55,220 --> 00:36:58,199
I'll have you know, I was
the first Negro female

567
00:36:58,224 --> 00:37:01,384
student at West Virginia
University Graduate School.

568
00:37:02,100 --> 00:37:05,077
On any given day,
I analyze the manometer levels

569
00:37:05,102 --> 00:37:07,774
for air displacement
friction and velocity.

570
00:37:08,310 --> 00:37:11,686
And compute over 10,000
calculations by cosine,

571
00:37:11,711 --> 00:37:14,664
square root and lately
Analytic Geometry.

572
00:37:14,790 --> 00:37:17,839
By hand. There are 20 bright,

573
00:37:17,864 --> 00:37:20,574
highly capable Negro women in the
West Computing Group,

574
00:37:21,160 --> 00:37:23,560
and we're proud to be doing our
part for the country.

575
00:37:24,361 --> 00:37:25,485
So, yes

576
00:37:25,510 --> 00:37:28,190
They let women do some things at NASA,
Mr. Johnson.

577
00:37:28,450 --> 00:37:30,000
And it's not because we wear skirts

578
00:37:31,160 --> 00:37:33,180
It's because we wear glasses

579
00:37:34,540 --> 00:37:35,650
Have a good day

580
00:37:50,015 --> 00:37:54,230
Scott, welcome to Langley.
Welcome to Langley.

581
00:37:54,554 --> 00:37:56,554
Right here, Gentlemen

582
00:38:06,645 --> 00:38:08,645
That's Alan Shepard.

583
00:38:08,870 --> 00:38:11,560
US Navy pilot. He could be
the first man in space.

584
00:38:11,720 --> 00:38:14,570
That's Scott Carpenter and
Walter Schirra.

585
00:38:14,730 --> 00:38:15,810
Also Navy pilots.

586
00:38:16,340 --> 00:38:18,460
All under 5'11", 180 lbs.

587
00:38:19,180 --> 00:38:20,205
IQs over 130.

588
00:38:20,430 --> 00:38:23,004
And handsome must
be a requirement too.

589
00:38:23,090 --> 00:38:25,682
How could you possibly be
ogling these white men?

590
00:38:25,807 --> 00:38:29,044
It's equal rights. I have the
right to see fine in every color.

591
00:38:30,030 --> 00:38:31,590
That's John Glenn.

592
00:38:31,750 --> 00:38:33,720
He's the only Marine Corps pilot.

593
00:38:33,800 --> 00:38:35,870
Gentlemen, if we may..
Much to see around here.

594
00:38:36,280 --> 00:38:37,930
We haven't shaken all the hands yet.

595
00:38:38,080 --> 00:38:40,752
- We have a fairly tight itinerary, Colonel.
- Ruth, it's fine.

596
00:38:40,777 --> 00:38:42,890
- He's coming straight.
- Look around ahead.

597
00:38:43,015 --> 00:38:45,665
Ladies. Didn't wanna
run off without saying hello

598
00:38:45,700 --> 00:38:48,233
They seem to be
in a big rush around here.

599
00:38:48,420 --> 00:38:50,719
The Russians certainly aren't
slowing down any.

600
00:38:50,720 --> 00:38:53,419
They can't build the refrigerator, how
the heck they beat us into space?

601
00:38:55,120 --> 00:38:56,360
What do you ladies do for NASA?

602
00:38:56,400 --> 00:38:59,010
- Calculate your trajectories.
Launch and landing.

603
00:38:59,035 --> 00:39:01,244
- I can't get anywhere without the numbers.
- No, sir.

604
00:39:01,770 --> 00:39:03,210
Mary Jackson, Mr. Glenn.

605
00:39:04,200 --> 00:39:06,760
Engineering. And I'm proud as
the devil to be workin' with you.

606
00:39:07,100 --> 00:39:08,190
Thank you, Mary.

607
00:39:08,214 --> 00:39:09,669
John!

608
00:39:10,270 --> 00:39:11,960
- I must take it inside
- Yes, sir.

609
00:39:11,984 --> 00:39:13,589
Guys!

610
00:39:51,330 --> 00:39:53,065
Mr. Harrison wants you
to confirm launch

611
00:39:53,090 --> 00:39:55,024
and landing for the
Redstone Rocket test.

612
00:40:00,110 --> 00:40:03,470
I cannot work on what I cannot see,
Mr. Stafford.

613
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:05,199
It's illegible.

614
00:40:05,200 --> 00:40:06,982
Those numbers have already been
confirmed by two engineers

615
00:40:07,007 --> 00:40:08,853
in this department, and myself.

616
00:40:08,878 --> 00:40:11,014
This is more or less
a dummy check.

617
00:40:47,290 --> 00:40:50,630
This one, like make a two. Make
a double. OK? Get it?

618
00:40:54,200 --> 00:40:56,050
No one thought to measure these things.

619
00:40:56,680 --> 00:40:58,160
I'm afraid, not. Sir.

620
00:40:59,570 --> 00:41:01,070
Would you like us to stop?

621
00:41:01,920 --> 00:41:03,410
No. No, just..

622
00:41:04,140 --> 00:41:06,240
I see, no. Just keep going.

623
00:41:07,880 --> 00:41:08,890
In fact

624
00:41:08,970 --> 00:41:11,410
- Use.. Use the big hammer
- Yes, sir.

625
00:41:11,830 --> 00:41:14,160
Come on, use the big hammer.
You heard the man. Let's go!

626
00:41:41,250 --> 00:41:42,590
Ma'am.

627
00:41:44,510 --> 00:41:46,330
Our runner can pick up your work, Dorothy.

628
00:41:47,620 --> 00:41:49,460
You need to be workin',
not walkin'.

629
00:41:49,490 --> 00:41:52,380
Oh! It's break time, ma'am.
No trouble at all.

630
00:41:52,480 --> 00:41:54,090
Well, since you made the trip

631
00:41:54,760 --> 00:41:56,300
you can take that batch over there

632
00:41:57,430 --> 00:41:59,130
Sure thing, Mrs. Mitchell.

633
00:42:02,260 --> 00:42:03,698
You need somethin' else?

634
00:42:03,723 --> 00:42:05,224
Yes, ma'am.

635
00:42:05,690 --> 00:42:08,370
I was wondering if you knew what
they're building over in the Tech Wing.

636
00:42:11,080 --> 00:42:12,890
It's called an IBM.

637
00:42:13,260 --> 00:42:14,260
A mainframe machine.

638
00:42:15,410 --> 00:42:18,210
Apparently, it can do our calculations
in a fraction of the time.

639
00:42:20,370 --> 00:42:21,870
Guess that's good for NASA.

640
00:42:25,610 --> 00:42:27,930
Hurry on, now.
Best if you do it in one trip.

641
00:42:45,580 --> 00:42:46,660
Excuse me

642
00:43:31,095 --> 00:43:32,245
Is that correct?

643
00:43:33,869 --> 00:43:35,169
Yeah

644
00:43:41,945 --> 00:43:43,645
Whose work is that?

645
00:43:45,270 --> 00:43:46,970
I said, whose work is that?!

646
00:43:50,110 --> 00:43:51,300
Katherine Goble, sir.

647
00:43:56,430 --> 00:43:59,100
How did you know the Redstone
couldn't support orbital flight?

648
00:43:59,124 --> 00:44:00,449
That's classified information

649
00:44:00,450 --> 00:44:01,810
It's top secret.

650
00:44:02,230 --> 00:44:04,729
Well, it's no secret why the
Redstone test keep failing

651
00:44:04,730 --> 00:44:07,613
its flight for sub-orbital flight,
but it can't handle the weight of the capsule

652
00:44:07,638 --> 00:44:09,304
and push it into space.

653
00:44:10,120 --> 00:44:11,770
Numbers don't lie.

654
00:44:12,480 --> 00:44:14,350
And you figured it all out with this?

655
00:44:16,200 --> 00:44:17,360
Half the data is redacted

656
00:44:18,930 --> 00:44:22,030
What's there tells the story
if you read between the lines.

657
00:44:22,470 --> 00:44:25,310
The distance from launch to orbit, we know.
Then mass we know.

658
00:44:25,340 --> 00:44:27,400
The Mercury Capsule weight, we know.

659
00:44:27,440 --> 00:44:30,080
And the speeds are there.. In the data.

660
00:44:30,850 --> 00:44:32,060
You did the math.

661
00:44:32,684 --> 00:44:34,084
Yes, sir.

662
00:44:34,560 --> 00:44:35,910
I looked beyond.

663
00:44:38,470 --> 00:44:40,600
And how do you know about the
Atlas rocket?

664
00:44:43,690 --> 00:44:45,180
That's not math.

665
00:44:45,990 --> 00:44:48,710
That data's not here. Like he said,
it's classified.

666
00:44:54,980 --> 00:44:56,440
I held it up to the light.

667
00:44:57,330 --> 00:44:59,640
- You held it up to the light?
- Yes, sir.

668
00:45:05,030 --> 00:45:06,620
Yep. There it is.

669
00:45:08,440 --> 00:45:09,470
Atlas

670
00:45:10,320 --> 00:45:11,490
What's your name?

671
00:45:11,800 --> 00:45:13,240
Katherine Goble.

672
00:45:14,490 --> 00:45:16,655
- Are you a spy, Katherine?
- Am I what?

673
00:45:16,680 --> 00:45:19,124
- I'm saying, are you a Russian spy?
- No, sir.

674
00:45:19,740 --> 00:45:20,980
I'm not Russian.

675
00:45:22,710 --> 00:45:24,300
She's not Russian, sir.

676
00:45:26,210 --> 00:45:28,067
All right then, we have
nothing to lose here.

677
00:45:28,092 --> 00:45:30,587
Give her everything she needs
to work on Shepard's trajectories.

678
00:45:30,612 --> 00:45:32,244
Without redaction.
Are we clear now?

679
00:45:32,290 --> 00:45:33,870
Right.
Are we sure about this?

680
00:45:34,250 --> 00:45:35,790
What's the issue, Paul?
You heard her.

681
00:45:36,490 --> 00:45:37,700
She's not a spy.

682
00:45:38,790 --> 00:45:40,494
I.. I just don't think it's a good idea.

683
00:45:40,719 --> 00:45:42,464
You know what I think is a good idea?

684
00:45:42,960 --> 00:45:44,050
Darker ink.

685
00:45:44,460 --> 00:45:46,970
I think darker ink is a good idea.
Ruth, could pass it along?

686
00:45:46,994 --> 00:45:48,049
Yes, sir.

687
00:45:48,250 --> 00:45:50,060
- Thank you, Katherine
- Thank you, sir.

688
00:45:57,010 --> 00:45:58,460
This interrogation is over

689
00:46:17,520 --> 00:46:19,719
You can probably get to the
moon and back with this.

690
00:46:19,720 --> 00:46:21,419
Just not the bathroom.

691
00:46:21,420 --> 00:46:23,025
At least they're not
blind to what you do.

692
00:46:23,050 --> 00:46:24,454
It's not going to matter soon.

693
00:46:24,960 --> 00:46:27,050
This IBM's going to put us all out of work.

694
00:46:28,330 --> 00:46:29,670
What can we do about it?

695
00:46:30,610 --> 00:46:31,800
Only one thing to do

696
00:46:32,650 --> 00:46:34,500
Learn all we can.
Make ourselves valuable.

697
00:46:35,010 --> 00:46:37,623
Somewhere down the line a human being's
going to have to push the buttons.

698
00:46:37,648 --> 00:46:38,684
That's right.

699
00:46:40,920 --> 00:46:42,020
Oh, mercy

700
00:46:43,020 --> 00:46:44,208
Well, she must be lost.

701
00:46:44,233 --> 00:46:47,794
NASA doesn't commission females
for the Engineer Training Program.

702
00:46:48,530 --> 00:46:52,210
That position is available to any
qualified applicant.

703
00:46:52,500 --> 00:46:54,999
Right. Except you don't have
the educational requirements.

704
00:46:55,000 --> 00:46:57,750
I have a Bachelors Degree in
Mathematics and Physical Sciences.

705
00:46:57,775 --> 00:46:59,794
It's the same as most
engineers around here.

706
00:46:59,970 --> 00:47:04,163
Well, we now require advanced extension
courses through the University of Virginia.

707
00:47:04,188 --> 00:47:06,804
It's in the Employee Handbook.
An addendum.

708
00:47:07,500 --> 00:47:08,650
Case you haven't read it

709
00:47:09,560 --> 00:47:12,740
Every time we have a chance to get
ahead, they move the finish line.

710
00:47:12,765 --> 00:47:15,083
I just follow the rules around here.
And I expect..

711
00:47:15,108 --> 00:47:17,368
Everyone who works for
me to follow them as well.

712
00:47:17,800 --> 00:47:20,410
There are no special circumstances
for anyone.

713
00:47:20,880 --> 00:47:23,340
You all should be thankful,
you have jobs at all.

714
00:47:29,190 --> 00:47:30,800
"For those that cannot attend classes

715
00:47:31,050 --> 00:47:32,910
at the University of Virginia,

716
00:47:32,970 --> 00:47:36,900
Advanced Extension Courses are
available at Hampton High School."

717
00:47:38,030 --> 00:47:39,760
That's still a segregated school, Mary

718
00:47:40,460 --> 00:47:43,870
Virginia acts like Brown vs. Board
of Education never happened.

719
00:47:43,890 --> 00:47:48,620
They'll never gonna allow a colored woman
just take classes at an all white school!

720
00:47:49,180 --> 00:47:52,190
- Sounds about right.
- That's all you're gonna say?

721
00:47:52,300 --> 00:47:54,058
Well, I'm not going to sit
here all day and listen to you

722
00:47:54,083 --> 00:47:56,364
complain about the way things
are, we're tryin to play cards.

723
00:47:56,810 --> 00:47:59,590
Petition the court. Fight for what
you want. But quit talking about it

724
00:48:03,080 --> 00:48:04,800
- I've been complaining?
- For days

725
00:48:04,824 --> 00:48:06,124
Ladies

726
00:48:07,060 --> 00:48:08,310
Not one more peep about work.

727
00:48:08,900 --> 00:48:10,270
Deal me in

728
00:48:10,630 --> 00:48:12,370
Katherine,
come on

729
00:48:13,240 --> 00:48:14,510
You

730
00:48:14,570 --> 00:48:17,070
Yeah! I needed this!
Thank you!

731
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:22,070
Don't give her any more Katherine

732
00:48:22,370 --> 00:48:24,200
I can't. She drank it all.

733
00:48:24,424 --> 00:48:26,424
Yes.
I'm fine

734
00:48:26,870 --> 00:48:28,700
I'm as fine as I've ever been.

735
00:48:28,725 --> 00:48:31,224
You're as drunk as you've ever been.

736
00:48:32,120 --> 00:48:34,400
Come on! Let's dance, girls.

737
00:48:34,824 --> 00:48:37,124
Come on, Kath!
Let's dance.

738
00:48:37,148 --> 00:48:38,284
Go dance, Katherine.

739
00:48:38,285 --> 00:48:40,784
Come on!

740
00:48:40,785 --> 00:48:42,052
We're gonna teach you how

741
00:48:42,077 --> 00:48:47,354
Keep going, here! All right.
Slow! Here slow down.

742
00:49:09,554 --> 00:49:19,554
Segregation must go!

743
00:49:21,920 --> 00:49:24,880
Don't pay attention to any of that. We're
not part of that trouble. Go on.

744
00:49:36,585 --> 00:49:37,585
Leonard..

745
00:49:37,610 --> 00:49:39,270
We must have done it.

746
00:49:43,355 --> 00:49:45,555
We don't want any trouble in here.

747
00:49:46,380 --> 00:49:47,980
Oh! I'm not here for any trouble. Ma'am.

748
00:49:48,080 --> 00:49:49,450
What are you here for?

749
00:49:50,630 --> 00:49:51,680
A book.

750
00:49:51,780 --> 00:49:54,260
You have books in the colored section.

751
00:49:55,140 --> 00:49:57,050
It doesn't have what I'm looking for.

752
00:49:57,170 --> 00:49:58,950
Well, that's just the way it is.

753
00:50:04,080 --> 00:50:05,106
Well, you know better...

754
00:50:05,107 --> 00:50:07,330
Get your hands off my boys.
Don't touch them.

755
00:50:08,490 --> 00:50:09,730
You have a blessed day.

756
00:50:18,955 --> 00:50:22,220
Separate and equal are
two different things.

757
00:50:22,360 --> 00:50:24,215
Just cause it's the way
doesn't make it right.

758
00:50:25,165 --> 00:50:26,215
Understand?

759
00:50:27,239 --> 00:50:28,239
Yes, mamma.

760
00:50:28,275 --> 00:50:33,155
You act right, you are right.
That's for certain. Understand?

761
00:50:33,579 --> 00:50:34,879
Yes, mamma.

762
00:50:40,840 --> 00:50:42,150
You took that book, mamma?

763
00:50:42,774 --> 00:50:44,774
Son, I pay taxes.

764
00:50:44,815 --> 00:50:46,830
And taxes pay for everything
in that library.

765
00:50:46,854 --> 00:50:48,854
You can't take something
you've already paid for.

766
00:50:53,675 --> 00:50:56,515
FORTRAN is a new and exciting language..

767
00:50:57,315 --> 00:51:00,325
Used by programmers to communicate
with computers...

768
00:51:00,790 --> 00:51:04,285
It's exciting, as it's the way
of the future.

769
00:51:05,145 --> 00:51:06,545
And everybody smile.

770
00:51:06,570 --> 00:51:08,010
