01:13:52,850 --> 01:13:54,229
Gus Grissom's coordinates..

1024
01:13:54,253 --> 01:13:57,663
I'd like to get a jump on
John Glenn's trajectory.

1025
01:13:58,360 --> 01:14:00,420
Do you have any idea what you're asking?

1026
01:14:00,421 --> 01:14:02,990
An orbital launch
with an Atlas Rocket is going to take time.

1027
01:14:03,450 --> 01:14:04,790
Is there a problem?

1028
01:14:06,920 --> 01:14:08,590
Mr. Harrison...

1029
01:14:09,010 --> 01:14:10,720
I was wondering....

1030
01:14:10,720 --> 01:14:14,260
I've been wondering my whole life.
So just... Spit it out.

1031
01:14:14,280 --> 01:14:16,380
Well, sir.

1032
01:14:18,570 --> 01:14:21,210
I'd like to get a jump on
John Glenn's trajectory.

1033
01:14:21,330 --> 01:14:24,130
This isn't about plugging in numbers,
this is about inventing the math.

1034
01:14:24,180 --> 01:14:26,844
I think we talked about that, right?
It doesn't exist.

1035
01:14:26,869 --> 01:14:28,074
I can do it, sir.

1036
01:14:28,140 --> 01:14:31,140
Do you know any idea how exacting
these calculations have to be?

1037
01:14:31,760 --> 01:14:34,420
It's like shooting a sawed-off shotgun
from a thousand feet,

1038
01:14:34,445 --> 01:14:37,259
and getting that one beebee through a hole
so tiny, you can't even see it.

1039
01:14:37,260 --> 01:14:38,984
I'm an excellent shot, sir.

1040
01:14:39,270 --> 01:14:41,230
How about Grissom's numbers. Paul?

1041
01:14:42,220 --> 01:14:43,570
They've been spot on.

1042
01:14:46,400 --> 01:14:47,870
Give Glenn's orbit a go.

1043
01:14:49,110 --> 01:14:51,100
But you run it all through Stafford.
Understood?

1044
01:14:51,101 --> 01:14:52,145
Yes, sir.

1045
01:14:52,370 --> 01:14:54,090
Thank you.

1046
01:14:57,780 --> 01:14:59,510
Computers don't author reports.

1047
01:15:06,688 --> 01:15:08,342
Capcom, this is Liberty Bell 7

1048
01:15:09,395 --> 01:15:10,380
loud and clear

1049
01:15:12,419 --> 01:15:14,142
ok, it's nice ride up to now

1050
01:15:23,700 --> 01:15:26,750
Liberty Bell 7 capsule is taking on water.

1051
01:15:27,020 --> 01:15:32,630
Gus Grissom is out of the capsule. Rescuers
are now going to pull him from the Ocean waves.

1052
01:15:33,070 --> 01:15:35,640
Unfortunately,
Liberty Bell 7 capsule..

1053
01:15:36,064 --> 01:15:37,664
.. Is lost.

1054
01:15:48,270 --> 01:15:51,740
Mr. Harrison, Taxpayer money sank in
the ocean along with your capsule.

1055
01:15:51,820 --> 01:15:54,540
What makes you think you can
bring John Glenn home safely?

1056
01:15:55,190 --> 01:15:58,860
Let me say first that discovery is never
for the sake of discovery, Gentlemen,

1057
01:15:58,870 --> 01:16:00,510
but for the sake of human survival.

1058
01:16:01,600 --> 01:16:03,170
It will always come with the risk.

1059
01:16:05,550 --> 01:16:09,650
Whoever gets there first, will make the rules.
That's been true of every civilization. And so..

1060
01:16:10,480 --> 01:16:13,420
I think the bigger question for
this body to consider is..

1061
01:16:13,444 --> 01:16:16,800
Who do you want calling the shots in space?

1062
01:16:17,900 --> 01:16:19,900
We have to know what's out there, Senator.

1063
01:16:20,660 --> 01:16:24,240
We have to touch the stars. If
only to ensure our own survival.

1064
01:16:24,265 --> 01:16:26,054
And only a man can do that.

1065
01:16:28,380 --> 01:16:30,510
We'll get John Glenn home safely
because we have to,

1066
01:16:32,310 --> 01:16:34,010
because he has to tell us what he saw.

1067
01:16:38,120 --> 01:16:39,890
The Redstone Rocket went straight up.

1068
01:16:40,360 --> 01:16:41,410
But the capsule..

1069
01:16:41,630 --> 01:16:44,250
.. Didn't have enough speed to go
into orbit. So came back down.

1070
01:16:44,940 --> 01:16:48,050
Essentially it's a triangle..
Earth, sub-orbit, Earth.

1071
01:16:48,430 --> 01:16:49,810
That math was known.

1072
01:16:49,890 --> 01:16:52,450
That took Shepard,
took Grissom.

1073
01:16:53,300 --> 01:16:55,160
That cannot take Glenn.

1074
01:16:56,040 --> 01:16:57,600
Now, The Atlas Rocket..

1075
01:16:58,470 --> 01:17:01,475
That can push us into orbit.
It goes up

1076
01:17:01,500 --> 01:17:04,414
delivers the capsule
into an elliptical orbit.

1077
01:17:04,450 --> 01:17:05,788
Earth's gravity keeps pulling it,

1078
01:17:05,813 --> 01:17:08,174
but it's going so fast that
it keeps missing the Earth.

1079
01:17:08,770 --> 01:17:10,130
That's how it stays in orbit.

1080
01:17:11,050 --> 01:17:12,870
Now, Getting it back down...

1081
01:17:14,080 --> 01:17:15,880
That's the math we don't know.

1082
01:17:17,900 --> 01:17:19,060
Yes, Katherine

1083
01:17:19,070 --> 01:17:21,718
So, the capsule will spin
around the Earth forever,

1084
01:17:21,743 --> 01:17:23,774
because there's nothing
to slow it down?

1085
01:17:24,340 --> 01:17:28,660
That's right. Slowing it down at precisely
the right moment,

1086
01:17:28,810 --> 01:17:30,450
by precisely the right amount

1087
01:17:30,460 --> 01:17:31,590
That is the task.

1088
01:17:34,600 --> 01:17:35,760
Yes, Katherine

1089
01:17:35,840 --> 01:17:42,920
So, it means to move from an
elliptical orbit.. To a parabolic orbit?

1090
01:17:43,170 --> 01:17:45,700
Yes.
That's the Go/ No Go.

1091
01:17:47,020 --> 01:17:48,790
Now, this point is a pin head.

1092
01:17:49,640 --> 01:17:52,900
- We bring him in too soon..
- He burns up on reentry.

1093
01:17:53,501 --> 01:17:57,630
That's right. We bring him too late,
and he's pushed out of Earth's gravity.

1094
01:17:57,770 --> 01:18:00,740
Any changes to mass, weight, speed, time,

1095
01:18:01,300 --> 01:18:07,350
distance, friction... or a puff of wind..
Would alter the Go/No Go.

1096
01:18:07,730 --> 01:18:10,580
And we start our calculations.. Over

1097
01:18:11,304 --> 01:18:12,804
Yes.

1098
01:18:12,880 --> 01:18:17,257
So, we need to be able to
choose this re-entry point.

1099
01:18:17,882 --> 01:18:20,904
This Go/No Go.
This has to be exact.

1100
01:18:21,250 --> 01:18:22,330
Sam

1101
01:18:22,600 --> 01:18:26,210
These are the latest Redstone numbers
and current capsule data.

1102
01:18:26,350 --> 01:18:28,430
Obviously, we know the launch spot

1103
01:18:28,710 --> 01:18:32,766
The Pentagon Briefing should illuminate
where the Navy needs the recovery zone.

1104
01:18:32,791 --> 01:18:34,814
When we work backwards from there.

1105
01:18:35,380 --> 01:18:37,920
And the rest is on us.
So, let's get to work.

1106
01:18:38,980 --> 01:18:41,816
- Mr. Stafford.
- What, Katherine?

1107
01:18:41,841 --> 01:18:45,514
If I could attend the briefings, I
would be more useful to the project.

1108
01:18:45,540 --> 01:18:47,630
Pentagon briefing is a closed door.

1109
01:18:47,680 --> 01:18:50,300
Yes. But if we don't
have the information,

1110
01:18:51,010 --> 01:18:54,822
of the changes.. We can't keep up.
I need those changes as they occur.

1111
01:18:54,847 --> 01:18:57,505
- As you said, it's a pin head.
- Katherine, that's the job.

1112
01:18:57,530 --> 01:19:00,840
You asked for this assignment.
So just calculate with what you have.

1113
01:19:01,720 --> 01:19:03,460
Or we'll find someone who can.

1114
01:19:10,500 --> 01:19:11,820
OK.

1115
01:19:24,350 --> 01:19:25,570
That'a girl.

1116
01:19:26,475 --> 01:19:28,775
And what the hell are you doing?
You can't be in here

1117
01:19:29,099 --> 01:19:30,299
Who are you?

1118
01:19:30,300 --> 01:19:32,320
I'm with the West Computing Group.

1119
01:19:32,920 --> 01:19:34,254
Dorothy Vaughan, sir.

1120
01:19:34,279 --> 01:19:36,424
Well, this is a very
delicate piece of equipment.

1121
01:19:36,490 --> 01:19:39,170
I'm sorry, sir.
I'm just trying to be helpful.

1122
01:19:39,194 --> 01:19:40,894
Bill, we've got numbers.

1123
01:19:42,920 --> 01:19:44,650
What kind of numbers?

1124
01:19:48,960 --> 01:19:50,570
Well, I'll be.

1125
01:19:51,310 --> 01:19:52,950
What's your name again?

1126
01:19:53,270 --> 01:19:54,830
Dorothy Vaughan.

1127
01:19:55,620 --> 01:19:57,060
Dorothy Vaughan...

1128
01:20:04,170 --> 01:20:06,875
Sir, the parameters
for Friendship 7.

1129
01:20:06,900 --> 01:20:10,504
Oh, this is all moot. We're
altering the window on the capsule.

1130
01:20:10,640 --> 01:20:11,712
When did this happen?

1131
01:20:11,737 --> 01:20:13,944
6 minutes ago. The mass is changing.
Start over.

1132
01:20:13,968 --> 01:20:17,640
Sir.. If I could attend briefings..
I could stay current..

1133
01:20:17,650 --> 01:20:19,830
Katherine, we've been through this.
It is not possible.

1134
01:20:19,920 --> 01:20:21,460
There's no protocol for women attending.

1135
01:20:21,910 --> 01:20:24,203
There's no protocol for a man
circling the Earth either, sir.

1136
01:20:24,228 --> 01:20:26,094
OK. That's just
the way things are.

1137
01:21:01,030 --> 01:21:04,200
Colonel Glenn's launch coordinates
accounting for the window change, sir.

1138
01:21:04,290 --> 01:21:07,289
I've told you this: Computers don't
author reports. Fix it.

1139
01:21:07,335 --> 01:21:09,435
Those are my calculations.
My name should be on it.

1140
01:21:09,559 --> 01:21:11,159
But it is not the way this works.

1141
01:21:11,760 --> 01:21:13,790
Paul.
What's happening here?

1142
01:21:13,791 --> 01:21:16,620
Mr. Harrison,
I'd like to attend today's briefing.

1143
01:21:16,720 --> 01:21:19,460
- Why's that?
- Well, sir, the data changes so fast.

1144
01:21:19,550 --> 01:21:23,620
The capsule changes. The weight and the
landing zones are all changing everyday.

1145
01:21:24,000 --> 01:21:27,390
I do my work, you attend these briefings.
I have to start all over.

1146
01:21:27,780 --> 01:21:29,850
Colonel Glenn launches in a few weeks.

1147
01:21:30,290 --> 01:21:31,860
We don't have the math figured out yet.

1148
01:21:32,775 --> 01:21:35,374
- Why is it she can't attend?
- Because she doesn't have clearance, Al.

1149
01:21:35,375 --> 01:21:38,674
I can not do my work effectively
if I do not have all of the data,

1150
01:21:38,675 --> 01:21:40,780
and all of the information
as soon as it's available.

1151
01:21:40,870 --> 01:21:42,469
I need to be in that room,
hearing what you hear.

1152
01:21:42,470 --> 01:21:45,665
Pentagon Briefings are not for civilians.
It requires the highest clearance.

1153
01:21:45,689 --> 01:21:47,289
I feel like I'm the best person
to present my calculations

1154
01:21:47,380 --> 01:21:49,280
- You're not gonna let this go are you?
- No, I'm not

1155
01:21:49,304 --> 01:21:52,804
Let her in? She's a woman.
There's no protocol for a woman attending.

1156
01:21:52,828 --> 01:21:54,828
Okay, I get that part, Paul.

1157
01:21:57,470 --> 01:22:01,130
But within these walls,
who... makes the rules?

1158
01:22:01,260 --> 01:22:06,370
You, sir. You're the boss.
You just have to act like one. Sir.

1159
01:22:15,230 --> 01:22:16,370
You keep quiet.

1160
01:22:17,300 --> 01:22:18,679
Thank you.

1161
01:22:19,204 --> 01:22:20,794
Good morning.

1162
01:22:21,520 --> 01:22:22,990
Gentlemen

1163
01:22:31,660 --> 01:22:35,270
This is Katherine Goble with our
Trajectory and Launch Window Division.

1164
01:22:36,040 --> 01:22:37,850
Her work is pertinent to
today's proceedings.

1165
01:22:39,590 --> 01:22:42,700
Come on.
Go get her a chair.

1166
01:22:44,310 --> 01:22:45,747
We have a confirmed
launch window..

1167
01:22:45,772 --> 01:22:47,145
- Give her your chair.
- Yes, sir.

1168
01:22:47,370 --> 01:22:50,730
We have a confirmed launch window for
friendship 7. Let's discuss a landing zone.

1169
01:22:51,460 --> 01:22:53,400
The Navy needs a singular landing zone.

1170
01:22:53,640 --> 01:22:56,300
20 miles square is what we can
service for retrieval.

1171
01:22:56,640 --> 01:22:59,310
Outside of that,
we risk the capsule's recovery.

1172
01:22:59,500 --> 01:23:01,430
We'd like 3 possible recovery areas.

1173
01:23:01,710 --> 01:23:03,500
We can't cover half the damn ocean.

1174
01:23:04,000 --> 01:23:06,630
With all due respect,
our capsule's being altered daily.

1175
01:23:07,870 --> 01:23:10,040
We're orbiting the Earth at...
what's the speed now?

1176
01:23:16,430 --> 01:23:18,390
17,544 miles per hour.

1177
01:23:19,130 --> 01:23:22,060
At the time the rocket delivers the
capsule into low space orbit.

1178
01:23:25,840 --> 01:23:27,470
That's one hell of a speeding ticket.

1179
01:23:29,880 --> 01:23:32,379
OK.
So we have the vehicle's speed,

1180
01:23:32,380 --> 01:23:36,270
the launch window and for argument's sake,
the landing zone is The Bahamas.

1181
01:23:37,160 --> 01:23:38,940
Should be enough to figure the Go/No Go?

1182
01:23:39,200 --> 01:23:42,465
- Yeah! In theory, sir.
- We need to be past theory at this point.

1183
01:23:42,590 --> 01:23:45,254
We'll be able to calculate a
Go/No Go with that information.

1184
01:23:45,350 --> 01:23:47,150
When exactly is that gonna happen?

1185
01:23:58,680 --> 01:23:59,690
Katherine.

1186
01:24:01,890 --> 01:24:03,450
Have a go at it?

1187
01:24:28,820 --> 01:24:30,960
The Go point for re-entry

1188
01:24:31,240 --> 01:24:34,730
is 2,990 miles

1189
01:24:35,280 --> 01:24:37,210
from where we want Colonel Glenn to land.

1190
01:24:38,040 --> 01:24:39,960
If we assume that's The Bahamas.

1191
01:24:41,000 --> 01:24:45,630
At 17,544 miles per hour..

1192
01:24:46,300 --> 01:24:47,440
Upon reentry..

1193
01:24:48,200 --> 01:24:49,530
370..

1194
01:24:50,200 --> 01:24:51,920
At a descent angle..

1195
01:24:52,240 --> 01:24:54,450
Of 46.56 ..

1196
01:24:55,480 --> 01:24:57,700
Degrees..
Distance..

1197
01:25:32,760 --> 01:25:34,500
OK!
So, that puts the landing zone at...

1198
01:25:34,540 --> 01:25:38,450
25.0667° North,

1199
01:25:38,460 --> 01:25:41,220
77.3333° West.

1200
01:25:42,970 --> 01:25:44,200
Which is here

1201
01:25:47,650 --> 01:25:51,240
Right here.
Give or take 20 square miles.

1202
01:25:56,590 --> 01:25:57,820
I like her numbers.

1203
01:25:59,190 --> 01:26:00,220
Thank you.

1204
01:26:01,460 --> 01:26:05,720
That of course is assuming the ..
Capsule hits the reentry point exactly

1205
01:26:06,320 --> 01:26:07,810
How do we insure that?

1206
01:26:09,160 --> 01:26:11,160
That's the math we don't
have yet, gentlemen.

1207
01:26:11,530 --> 01:26:12,880
We're working on it.

1208
01:26:15,250 --> 01:26:16,560
Katherine

1209
01:26:20,200 --> 01:26:22,699
What's it gonna take to make
this thing worth the price tag?

1210
01:26:22,700 --> 01:26:24,799
We're just getting up to speed here,
Mr. Harrison.

1211
01:26:24,823 --> 01:26:26,299
I need more man power.

1212
01:26:26,300 --> 01:26:28,125
I mean Programmers.
Folks to feed the cards.

1213
01:26:28,150 --> 01:26:30,564
Then get them, for crying out loud.
Right?

1214
01:26:30,940 --> 01:26:32,980
- You're the IBM man, right?
- Yes, sir.

1215
01:26:32,990 --> 01:26:35,487
Pull them out of the sky if you
have to, but let's get ahead of

1216
01:26:35,512 --> 01:26:37,934
- this thing. Or I'm not paying you.
- Understood

1217
01:26:41,360 --> 01:26:43,390
I got that one

1218
01:26:44,820 --> 01:26:46,420
I'm not paying any of you!

1219
01:26:56,140 --> 01:26:58,770
- Me?
- Temporarily. Yes.

1220
01:26:59,094 --> 01:27:01,094
We need the IBM for Glenn's launch.

1221
01:27:01,420 --> 01:27:04,570
The Lead Engineer says you're good
with the cards, programming and such.

1222
01:27:05,270 --> 01:27:06,598
What about the girls here?

1223
01:27:06,623 --> 01:27:10,504
Human computers can't calculate an
orbital flight in the time we have.

1224
01:27:10,900 --> 01:27:14,380
- They'll stay put for now.
- What about after "now"?

1225
01:27:15,170 --> 01:27:19,940
After the Glenn launch, NASA's
dissolvin' the Computing Groups.

1226
01:27:22,500 --> 01:27:24,320
I'm not accepting reassignment.

1227
01:27:24,400 --> 01:27:25,980
Unless, I bring my ladies with me.

1228
01:27:27,250 --> 01:27:28,263
Excuse me?

1229
01:27:28,488 --> 01:27:30,925
We're going to need a lot of
manpower to program that beast.

1230
01:27:30,950 --> 01:27:33,380
I can't do it alone.
My girls are ready

1231
01:27:34,040 --> 01:27:35,850
They can do the work.

1232
01:27:39,470 --> 01:27:44,330
Ladies!
We've been reassigned.

1233
01:27:45,960 --> 01:27:48,460
Leave your calculators.
You won't need them where we're going.

1234
01:28:48,915 --> 01:28:50,875
Welcome, ladies!

1235
01:29:01,130 --> 01:29:02,940
Do you know what your job is, Paul?

1236
01:29:04,710 --> 01:29:06,850
To find the genius among those geniuses.

1237
01:29:07,030 --> 01:29:08,680
To pull us all up.

1238
01:29:09,720 --> 01:29:14,210
We all get to the peak together,
or we.. Don't get there at all.

1239
01:29:17,510 --> 01:29:19,770
Yes. Well.
Good night, sir.

1240
01:29:49,030 --> 01:29:50,830
I don't know what time
I'm coming home.

1241
01:29:51,010 --> 01:29:52,650
The class ends at 9.

1242
01:29:56,020 --> 01:29:57,770
You got something to say?

1243
01:29:59,120 --> 01:30:00,740
Thought you might need these.

1244
01:30:04,050 --> 01:30:06,410
You can refill ‘em with any weight
lead you want.

1245
01:30:07,370 --> 01:30:10,200
See, you just hit the top like this.

1246
01:30:11,860 --> 01:30:13,030
Lead comes out

1247
01:30:14,100 --> 01:30:15,390
You put the new lead in..

1248
01:30:15,750 --> 01:30:18,690
And.. New pencil

1249
01:30:22,610 --> 01:30:24,560
You will make a fine engineer.

1250
01:30:25,520 --> 01:30:28,060
- You think so?
- Yes.

1251
01:30:29,040 --> 01:30:36,120
And nobody dare stand in the way of
Mary Jackson's dreams. Myself included.

1252
01:30:41,465 --> 01:30:44,465
- Don't make me mad again.
- Yes, ma'am.

1253
01:30:48,540 --> 01:30:50,330
And don't make me late either.

1254
01:30:50,990 --> 01:30:52,450
You don't really want me to make you?

1255
01:31:00,750 --> 01:31:04,044
Hi, gentlemen.
Tonight we discuss Planck–Einstein.

1256
01:31:04,069 --> 01:31:05,994
Wavelength relationships..

1257
01:31:10,170 --> 01:31:11,250
Yes?

1258
01:31:12,960 --> 01:31:15,800
I'm Mary Jackson.
I'm enrolled.

1259
01:31:17,800 --> 01:31:21,000
Well. The curriculum is not designed
for teaching... a woman.

1260
01:31:21,750 --> 01:31:23,640
Well, I imagine it's the same as
teaching a man.

1261
01:31:25,580 --> 01:31:29,220
I don't see a colored section.
Should I just take any seat?

1262
01:31:34,868 --> 01:31:36,668
Thank you.

1263
01:31:41,060 --> 01:31:42,400
OK.

1264
01:31:43,590 --> 01:31:45,260
Planck–Einstein...

1265
01:31:46,480 --> 01:31:52,120
The problem is when the capsule moves
from an elliptical orbit to a parabolic orbit.

1266
01:31:52,980 --> 01:31:54,990
There's no mathematical formula for that.

1267
01:31:55,480 --> 01:31:57,880
As we can calculate launch, landing

1268
01:31:57,920 --> 01:32:01,830
but without this conversion, the capsule
stays in orbit, we can't bring it back home.

1269
01:32:04,560 --> 01:32:06,530
Maybe we've been thinking about this
all wrong.

1270
01:32:06,690 --> 01:32:08,280
How's that?

1271
01:32:12,230 --> 01:32:14,060
Maybe it's not new math at all.

1272
01:32:15,900 --> 01:32:17,550
It could be old math.

1273
01:32:18,760 --> 01:32:21,790
Something that looks at the problem
numerically, and not theoretically

1274
01:32:22,700 --> 01:32:26,410
- Math is always dependable.
- For you it is.

1275
01:32:33,380 --> 01:32:34,540
Euler's Method.

1276
01:32:34,610 --> 01:32:36,420
- Euler's Method?
- Yes.

1277
01:32:36,420 --> 01:32:39,430
- That's ancient.
- But it works!

1278
01:32:39,920 --> 01:32:41,690
It works numerically.

1279
01:33:17,660 --> 01:33:19,360
That's it!

1280
01:33:21,240 --> 01:33:23,830
Let's type it up.

1281
01:33:48,945 --> 01:33:50,545
Dorothy.

1282
01:33:50,970 --> 01:33:52,670
Mrs. Mitchell.

1283
01:33:58,640 --> 01:34:00,320
You're working late today?

1284
01:34:01,530 --> 01:34:03,520
Seems always happened that way

1285
01:34:03,850 --> 01:34:05,690
Yes.
Seems to.

1286
01:34:14,205 --> 01:34:15,605
Thank you.

1287
01:34:18,680 --> 01:34:22,240
I hear the IBM is at full capacity.

1288
01:34:22,735 --> 01:34:24,435
You certainly have a knack for it

1289
01:34:25,160 --> 01:34:27,430
My father taught me a thing or
two about mechanics.

1290
01:34:28,850 --> 01:34:33,070
You know, I have a few girls in the East Group
that have an interest in learnin' more about it.

1291
01:34:33,160 --> 01:34:36,640
- It is the future.
- I may bring ‘em by, if it's all the same to you.

1292
01:34:38,220 --> 01:34:41,600
That's not my decision. Ma'am.
That would be the supervisor's.

1293
01:34:43,124 --> 01:34:45,124
Yes. That's true.

1294
01:34:45,720 --> 01:34:48,280
Well.
Good night, Mrs. Mitchell.

1295
01:34:50,410 --> 01:34:51,820
You know, Dorothy...

1296
01:34:53,640 --> 01:34:58,420
Despite what you may think..
I have nothin' against ya'll.

1297
01:34:59,300 --> 01:35:03,280
I know.
I know you probably believe that.

1298
01:35:16,125 --> 01:35:17,625
Goodnight, Katherine.

1299
01:35:18,450 --> 01:35:19,950
Good night!

1300
01:35:21,940 --> 01:35:24,530
- Mamma.
- Hey, baby

1301
01:35:24,550 --> 01:35:27,110
Hi!
Hey!

1302
01:35:28,710 --> 01:35:31,130
Please don't tell me I miss
someone's birthday

1303
01:35:31,154 --> 01:35:32,889
- No, you didn't
- No, you didn't, mamma

1304
01:35:32,890 --> 01:35:34,280
Madame...
Your seat.

1305
01:35:34,830 --> 01:35:39,360
Thank you
Well, is it my birthday?

1306
01:35:39,684 --> 01:35:41,384
No, mamma.

1307
01:35:42,130 --> 01:35:44,140
You're all look so pretty

1308
01:35:47,010 --> 01:35:48,870
Mamma,
What's going on?

1309
01:35:52,070 --> 01:35:53,270
Good evening, Katherine.

1310
01:35:58,980 --> 01:36:01,650
- So, you are not gonna say anything?
- It's not my place.

1311
01:36:04,260 --> 01:36:05,630
You, really?

1312
01:36:08,230 --> 01:36:10,130
Okay, I'm not going to do this all night...

1313
01:36:12,854 --> 01:36:14,854
Oh, mother of mercy.
That's for me?

1314
01:36:19,710 --> 01:36:20,830
Are you sad, Mamma?

1315
01:36:21,190 --> 01:36:24,430
- No! - It's okay, Mamma.
- He's a good man.

1316
01:36:24,430 --> 01:36:27,480
I know.
I know. I just. I can't help it.

1317
01:36:27,555 --> 01:36:29,055
He hasn't even asked you yet.

1318
01:36:30,480 --> 01:36:33,620
I know, but he is..
You are, right?

1319
01:36:33,715 --> 01:36:35,115
If ya'll let me.

1320
01:36:35,140 --> 01:36:37,150
Go on. She's already crying.

1321
01:36:38,750 --> 01:36:41,680
- This was my mother's ring.
- It is beautiful

1322
01:36:42,970 --> 01:36:46,160
- She and my father were married for..
- For 52 years.

1323
01:36:47,660 --> 01:36:49,930
I figure it's about as lucky as a ring
as you can get.

1324
01:36:51,590 --> 01:36:53,330
The day I met you, I called my mother...

1325
01:36:53,860 --> 01:36:57,040
I said: "Mom!
I met the woman I want to marry."

1326
01:36:57,064 --> 01:36:58,089
What'd she say?

1327
01:36:58,390 --> 01:37:00,890
She said: "She must be something,
Jimmy. Really something."

1328
01:37:00,914 --> 01:37:02,114
Then what'd you say?

1329
01:37:02,138 --> 01:37:07,938
I said: "No, She is more than Something,
She is Everything."

1330
01:37:11,150 --> 01:37:14,390
I planned on this being more romantic.
I'll make that up to you real soon.

1331
01:37:16,620 --> 01:37:20,770
But I know marrying you..
Includes me and the girls as well.

1332
01:37:22,850 --> 01:37:24,290
Amen to that.

1333
01:37:24,990 --> 01:37:26,100
I do.

1334
01:37:27,020 --> 01:37:29,050
- I didn't ask you yet.
- Hurry up!

1335
01:37:36,670 --> 01:37:39,880
No pain, please!
No, girls. No tears.

1336
01:37:44,020 --> 01:37:47,060
The Mercury Atlas Space vehicle,
which will putt John Glenn

1337
01:37:47,280 --> 01:37:48,850
the first American into Earth orbit,

1338
01:37:49,180 --> 01:37:52,060
has already undergone 5 unmanned
flight tests.

1339
01:37:52,310 --> 01:37:56,909
NASA has confirmed that the
IBM 790 data processing

1340
01:37:56,934 --> 01:38:01,054
system has been utilized to confirm all of the
mission's long and recovery system calculations.

1341
01:38:01,080 --> 01:38:04,880
The modifications and equipment installations
are progressing on the schedule.

1342
01:38:05,530 --> 01:38:06,470
Them, Here

1343
01:38:07,840 --> 01:38:09,820
- You wanted to see me, sir?
- Have a seat

1344
01:38:11,280 --> 01:38:12,840
Is there something wrong, Mr. Harrison?

1345
01:38:12,880 --> 01:38:14,290
No. There's nothing wrong.

1346
01:38:16,290 --> 01:38:19,510
In fact our IBM is churning out numbers
in fractions of the time any human can

1347
01:38:20,180 --> 01:38:21,830
Present company included.

1348
01:38:22,850 --> 01:38:24,320
That's good then.

1349
01:38:27,310 --> 01:38:28,730
Maybe.

1350
01:38:29,170 --> 01:38:32,460
The thing is, the Cape is now insisting on
doing all the backups down there. On site.

1351
01:38:34,480 --> 01:38:35,490
I see.

1352
01:38:35,560 --> 01:38:37,270
So, we won't be running backups here.

1353
01:38:38,780 --> 01:38:41,090
And truth be told, we can't keep up
with that IBM anyhow.

1354
01:38:44,930 --> 01:38:47,780
Long story short, we no longer need a..
Computer in this department.

1355
01:38:49,940 --> 01:38:51,810
Progress is a double edged sword.

1356
01:38:57,150 --> 01:38:59,467
Let's have you report back
to the West Group for now.

1357
01:38:59,492 --> 01:39:03,464
- I'll see if we can find another assignment.
- Thank you, sir.

1358
01:39:07,110 --> 01:39:11,500
Katherine, I'm..
I'm sorry about this

1359
01:39:13,330 --> 01:39:15,380
It's out of my hands, if you
can believe that.

1360
01:39:16,390 --> 01:39:17,880
I understand.

1361
01:39:41,610 --> 01:39:45,980
Katherine..
We heard you got engaged.

1362
01:39:46,420 --> 01:39:51,000
Yes.
That's thoughtful of you.

1363
01:39:56,240 --> 01:39:59,990
- They're lovely.
- Mr. Harrison's idea really.

1364
01:40:00,520 --> 01:40:02,700
Although I suspect his wife did
the picking out.

1365
01:40:03,660 --> 01:40:06,550
I can't imagine he has an eye
for anything but numbers..

1366
01:40:07,560 --> 01:40:12,740
Now, you have a great wedding.
You did good work around here, Katherine.

1367
01:40:47,100 --> 01:40:50,140
I don't think I felt a thing
the first time I did this.

1368
01:40:50,380 --> 01:40:52,970
I was so nervous.

1369
01:40:54,050 --> 01:40:57,990
- This is as beautiful as you were back then.
- You think so?

1370
01:40:58,450 --> 01:41:00,040
Just a little older.

1371
01:41:00,600 --> 01:41:04,040
And a little fuller...
But you look good.

1372
01:41:08,565 --> 01:41:10,465
Here we go. Again.

1373
01:41:20,490 --> 01:41:22,390
That'a girl

1374
01:41:25,080 --> 01:41:29,079
.. And Colonel John Glenn will be
the first American to orbit the Earth.

1375
01:41:29,280 --> 01:41:32,890
As you can see, there are thousands of
people here to witness this historic event

1376
01:41:34,570 --> 01:41:38,500
Paul, something's off here. These landing
coordinates don't match yesterday's.

1377
01:41:39,900 --> 01:41:42,290
The IBM just ran them.

1378
01:41:42,840 --> 01:41:46,760
So then the IBM was wrong yesterday, right?

1379
01:41:47,440 --> 01:41:49,310
Or the damn thing is wrong today.

1380
01:41:52,720 --> 01:41:56,730
Paul, Am I right?
- It appears so.

1381
01:41:59,778 --> 01:42:02,078
The IBM has been spot on up to this point, John.

1382
01:42:02,102 --> 01:42:04,202
But we'll run it again,
to see what it comes up with.

1383
01:42:04,590 --> 01:42:08,260
I'll be honest with you, Al
When I fly, I fly the machine,

1384
01:42:08,584 --> 01:42:10,584
Right now, it seems like this machine
is flying me.

1385
01:42:11,130 --> 01:42:13,500
We're on the same page, John.
Our guys are on it.

1386
01:42:13,700 --> 01:42:15,770
Let's get the girl to check the numbers.

1387
01:42:15,940 --> 01:42:18,240
- The girl?
- Yes, sir.

1388
01:42:20,010 --> 01:42:22,840
- You mean Katherine?
- Yes, sir. The smart one.

1389
01:42:23,250 --> 01:42:25,630
If she says they're good,
I'm ready to go.

1390
01:42:26,860 --> 01:42:28,960
- All right. We'll get into it.
- Roger!

1391
01:42:31,260 --> 01:42:34,860
Sam!
Go find Katherine Goble.

1392
01:42:34,900 --> 01:42:38,510
She needs to verify Glenn's Go/No Go
or we're staying on the ground.

1393
01:42:38,580 --> 01:42:40,679
Yes, sir.

1394
01:43:03,690 --> 01:43:05,090
I'm looking for Katherine Goble

1395
01:43:05,150 --> 01:43:08,400
- It's Katherine Johnson now.
- They need you to verify these coordinates.

1396
01:43:18,410 --> 01:43:20,540
All right.
Give her some space to work.

1397
01:43:23,790 --> 01:43:26,120
A truly historic day for America..

1398
01:43:26,840 --> 01:43:32,839
The country has waited for several months,
through many failed unmanned Atlas rocket tests

1399
01:43:32,840 --> 01:43:35,739
and 10 scheduled manned attempts,

1400
01:43:35,740 --> 01:43:40,039
which were canceled for various
mechanical or system complications.

1401
01:43:40,910 --> 01:43:46,950
All the final tests and checks are being conducted,
John Glenn is ready to board the Friendship 7.

1402
01:43:47,187 --> 01:43:49,120
But today we remain truly optimistic

1403
01:43:49,470 --> 01:43:51,265
and it's a go day in all regards

1404
01:43:52,109 --> 01:43:56,540
the capsule is ready, the rocket itself
is a OK, and the weather here at..

1405
01:43:57,385 --> 01:43:59,785
- Anything from Langley?
- Not yet.

1406
01:44:00,042 --> 01:44:04,331
We're being told the mission control at Nasa
is conducting a final check

1407
01:44:04,613 --> 01:44:08,973
of the launch and recovery coordinates
including the go/no-go calculations

1408
01:44:09,269 --> 01:44:11,823
so crucial to a safe and successful launch
and recovery

1409
01:44:12,220 --> 01:44:14,300
After years of waiting, and months of delays,

1410
01:44:14,900 --> 01:44:19,250
col. Glen is finally ready for that space flight
we've been waiting for with so much anticipation

1411
01:44:31,880 --> 01:44:33,615
- We are still a go.
- Yes, sir.

1412
01:44:38,744 --> 01:44:40,344
That's it.

1413
01:44:43,960 --> 01:44:46,430
What the devil are you doing?
Are you taking a break?

1414
01:45:33,485 --> 01:45:35,140
You have the time?

1415
01:46:06,665 --> 01:46:08,265
Sir.

1416
01:46:12,130 --> 01:46:13,930
Pad 14.

1417
01:46:25,450 --> 01:46:26,630
Katherine!

1418
01:46:31,560 --> 01:46:33,730
Come on

1419
01:46:36,320 --> 01:46:38,220
Sir, we've got Pad 14 on the box.

1420
01:46:38,390 --> 01:46:40,140
Alright, let me in there.

1421
01:46:43,140 --> 01:46:45,670
This is Langley.
We have the coordinates confirmed.

1422
01:46:46,094 --> 01:46:47,794
Standby, Langley.

1423
01:46:49,930 --> 01:46:53,350
We can confirm the Go/No Go
point for re-entry is..

1424
01:46:53,690 --> 01:47:05,290
16.11984 degrees latitude
- 165.2356 degrees longitude.

1425
01:47:06,080 --> 01:47:09,720
The launch window is a go.
The landing coordinates match.

1426
01:47:10,500 --> 01:47:11,940
That's very good news, Al.

1427
01:47:12,970 --> 01:47:15,570
It's a little hard to trust something
you can't look in the eyes.

1428
01:47:15,580 --> 01:47:18,570
That's right, Colonel.
Katherine did manage to calculate

1429
01:47:18,594 --> 01:47:21,194
a few decimal points further than that
hunk of metal.

1430
01:47:22,050 --> 01:47:25,270
Well, I'll take every digit ya got.
Be sure to thank her for me.

1431
01:47:25,370 --> 01:47:29,060
- Gentlemen! Let's launch this rocket.
- Good luck, Friendship 7.

1432
01:47:29,084 --> 01:47:30,829
God speed, Langley.

1433
01:47:33,930 --> 01:47:38,040
Here at Cape Canaveral the countdown
has resumed as Colonel John Glenn

1434
01:47:38,300 --> 01:47:43,070
is now aboard Friendship 7,
high above the Atlas rocket on Pad 14.

1435
01:47:43,640 --> 01:47:45,390
A height of over 93 feet ..

1436
01:47:47,330 --> 01:47:51,670
These pictures are from Cape Canaveral, Florida
Deck entry is now moving back.

1437
01:47:51,730 --> 01:47:52,810
We're go for launch.

1438
01:47:53,660 --> 01:47:56,460
The Mercury Spacecraft umbilical is out

1439
01:47:57,385 --> 01:47:59,085
T-10 seconds, and counting

1440
01:48:00,010 --> 01:48:03,740
8.. 7.. 6.. 5..

1441
01:48:03,830 --> 01:48:06,775
4.. 3.. 2..

1442
01:48:07,399 --> 01:48:10,299
1.. Zero.
Ignition.

1443
01:48:22,295 --> 01:48:24,045
It's getting bumpy along here.

1444
01:48:24,140 --> 01:48:26,335
Roger that.
You are in Max Q.

1445
01:48:26,359 --> 01:48:27,864
Roger that Capcom

1446
01:48:29,890 --> 01:48:31,985
Twenty seconds to SECO.

1447
01:48:32,009 --> 01:48:35,433
- The trajectory is still be "OK".
- Go for SECO.

1448
01:48:42,950 --> 01:48:45,610
Zero G. And I feel fine.

1449
01:48:45,634 --> 01:48:47,634
John Glenn reports everything looks good

1450
01:48:48,960 --> 01:48:51,305
Oh, that view is tremendous.

1451
01:48:52,985 --> 01:48:55,475
Roger that, Friendship 7.

1452
01:49:00,465 --> 01:49:03,220
- You are go for orbit.
- Thank you, Capcom!

1453
01:49:08,800 --> 01:49:12,420
All right. 10.5 hours to go.
If we make 7 round trips.

1454
01:49:13,940 --> 01:49:15,205
I could use a coffee.

1455
01:49:17,020 --> 01:49:20,320
Well, as we approach the end of day
here on the Eastern seaboard..

1456
01:49:20,690 --> 01:49:23,404
Colonel Glenn is just beginning
his third orbit.

1457
01:49:23,429 --> 01:49:26,244
Three quarters of the way
across the African continent.

1458
01:49:26,510 --> 01:49:30,780
We see he is currently over Zanzibar, which
is the next tracking station coming up.

1459
01:49:30,860 --> 01:49:32,950
Thankfully the Friendship 7 capsule is..

1460
01:49:41,490 --> 01:49:43,450
New assignment came down the pike.

1461
01:49:46,980 --> 01:49:51,260
Always changing round here.
It's hard to keep up.

1462
01:49:53,890 --> 01:49:56,680
Seems like they're gonna need
a permanent team to feed that IBM

1463
01:49:57,520 --> 01:50:00,600
- How big of a team?
- 30 to start.

1464
01:50:03,660 --> 01:50:05,830
Thank you for the information,
Mrs. Mitchell.

1465
01:50:07,170 --> 01:50:10,480
You're quite welcome... Mrs. Vaughan.

1466
01:50:55,360 --> 01:50:57,410
We have a warning light!

1467
01:50:57,420 --> 01:50:59,430
Capcom 7,
I have a warning light.

1468
01:50:59,720 --> 01:51:01,080
Standby, 7.

1469
01:51:01,530 --> 01:51:02,710
Sir, we have a warning light!

1470
01:51:06,990 --> 01:51:11,268
- What are we looking at, Paul?
- The heat shield may have come loose.

1471
01:51:11,293 --> 01:51:15,504
7, will you confirm the landing
bag is in the OFF position?

1472
01:51:15,950 --> 01:51:17,670
Affirmative, Capcom.

1473
01:51:18,180 --> 01:51:20,579
Al, we need to get him down, now
He could burn up on re-entry.

1474
01:51:30,180 --> 01:51:32,010
Come on, babies!

1475
01:51:32,130 --> 01:51:35,040
There's a man in space. We don't want to
miss it, so we gonna home.

1476
01:51:35,064 --> 01:51:36,289
Something's wrong with Glenn.

1477
01:51:36,290 --> 01:51:37,760
- Oh, my Goodness!
- What's going on?

1478
01:51:37,850 --> 01:51:40,190
- Let's go.
- Ya'll follow me.

1479
01:51:41,530 --> 01:51:46,860
We've just learned, the Friendship 7
is in danger of losing its heat shield.

1480
01:51:47,010 --> 01:51:50,880
Have you heard any banging noises?
Or anything of this type at higher rates?

1481
01:51:51,050 --> 01:51:52,430
That's a negative, Capcom.

1482
01:51:54,410 --> 01:51:56,088
Tell him not to jettison
the retro-package.

1483
01:51:56,413 --> 01:51:58,444
Tell him not to jettison
the retro-package.

1484
01:51:58,800 --> 01:52:02,730
NASA is confirming there is some sort of
malfunction with the capsule's heat shield,

1485
01:52:02,755 --> 01:52:04,364
and it may not stay in place.

1486
01:52:04,690 --> 01:52:10,170
If the heat shield is loose... The retro-
package straps might hold it in place.

1487
01:52:10,250 --> 01:52:12,940
- Will that work?
- It will work.

1488
01:52:13,590 --> 01:52:17,150
It will hold it until he reaches the
Go /No Go point. It will work!

1489
01:52:18,630 --> 01:52:20,620
He has to override the 05g.

1490
01:52:21,420 --> 01:52:23,310
Do it.

1491
01:52:23,400 --> 01:52:24,596
Friendship 7...

1492
01:52:24,621 --> 01:52:29,283
We're recommending that the retro-package
NOT, I repeat, NOT be jettisoned.

1493
01:52:29,808 --> 01:52:33,670
This means that you will have
to override the 05g switch.

1494
01:52:33,730 --> 01:52:36,580
Roger!
Is there a reason for this? Over.

1495
01:52:37,350 --> 01:52:38,530
Standby, 7.

1496
01:52:43,330 --> 01:52:44,520
Not at this time, 7.

1497
01:52:46,280 --> 01:52:49,850
Roger, that command.
I will make a manual 05g entry,

1498
01:52:50,520 --> 01:52:52,710
and bring the scope in.
